Figure S3, http://links.lww.com/QAD/A766, shows the distribution of all individual viral load measurements throughout the set-point window, stratiﬁed by SPVL and CD4þcell count.
These ﬁndings were relatively insensitive to the choice of smoothing method used (see Supplementary Material, http://links.lww.com/QAD/A766).

Patients were only included in the analysis if they had a minimum number (six) of CD4þcell counts so that smoothing could be reliably performed; the choice of minimum number of individual CD4þmeasurements used to estimate the smoothing model was also seen not to have an effect on the results (Supplementary Material, http://links.lww.com/QAD/A766).

Similarly, results were similar when considering only CD4þmeasurements prior to mono or dual ART initiation, or when considering only patients recruited after 1996 (Supple- mentary Material, http://links.lww.com/QAD/A766).

Substantial changes have been seen in population-level SPVL over time (Figure S2, http://links.lww.com/ QAD/A766), and similarly large differences can beobserved in the unstratiﬁed CD4þprogression rates between different time periods.

Comparing MSM/ bisexual men to other HIV transmission routes (79% via heterosexual sex, but also including people who inject drugs and one haemophiliac), there was little difference in the rate of CD4þprogression, although results indicate that MSM/bisexual men may progress more quickly to death once they reach a CD4þcell count of 200 cells/ ml (Supplementary Material, http://links.lww.com/QAD/ A766).

No signiﬁcant difference was found in CD4þ progression between men and women, but there were very few women in the sample and hence only unstratiﬁed analysis was possible (Supplementary Material, http://links.lww.com/QAD/A766).

This predictive model was able to broadly reproduce the true CD4þdynamics of the patients selected for validation, given their ﬁrst observed CD4þcategory (see Figure S6 and Supplementary Material for detail, http://links.lww.com/QAD/A766).2440 AIDS 2015, Vol 29 No 18

Our results suggest that if the patient’s SPVL is known, the frequency of CD4þmonitoring could be adapted to account for that, with a CD4þcell count test every 13–23, 6–12, 3–8 and 2–4 months for individuals with SPVL below 4.0, 4.0–4.5, 4.5–5.0 and at least 5.0 log10copies/ml, respectively (see Supplementary Material for detail, http://links.lww.com/QAD/A766).

In an additional sensitivity analysis including children transferred-in, signi ﬁ- cance of associations did not change, so transfer-in children were excluded from the main analysis (see Table S1, Supple- mental Digital Content, http://links.lww.com/QAI/A721).

Active tracing reduced the risk of being LTFU at the end of the study period by 38% (AHR 0.62 and 95% CI: 0.42 to0.91, and P= 0.014) (see Table S2, Supplemental Digital Content, http://links.lww.com/QAI/A721).TABLE 2.

Keywords:  sit-to-stand test, strength training, COPD Introduction Muscle weakness and peripheral muscle dysfunction are highly prevalent comorbidities  of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), contributing to exercise intolerance  and symptom intensity.1,2 Pulmonary rehabilitation (PR) has a well-established role in  the management of COPD patients with peripheral muscle dysfunction.3 Evidence-based  guidelines for PR recommend that the exercise component of the program includes endur - ance and strength training of the lower limbs.4 Strength training has a greater potential to  improve muscle mass and strength than with endurance training.5,6 In addition, strength  training also induces less dyspnea during the exercise period, making this strategy better  performed by patients with moderate-to-severe COPD, than with aerobic training.7Correspondence: Andrea Zanini Divisione di Medicina Interna a Indirizzo  Pneumologico, Ospedale Malcantonese,  Fondazione Giuseppe Rossi, 6980  Castelrotto, Switzerland Tel +41 91 611 3700 Fax +41 91 611 3701 Email azanini67@gmail.co m Journal name: International Journal of COPD Article Designation: ORIGINAL RESEARCH Y ear: 2015 Volume: 10 Running head verso: Zanini et al Running head recto: Sit-to-stand peripheral muscle strength in COPD DOI: http://dx.doi.org/10.2147/COPD.S91176

The National Cholesterol Education Program under the auspices  of the National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute published the Adult  Treatment Panel  (ATP) III Clinical Identification of the MetS in  2001 ( Table  1) (http://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/files/docs/guidelines/ atp3xsum.pdf).

The International Diabetes Federation (IDF) issued a consensus  statement in 2013 in which they further defined MetS and the criteria  for different races and ethnic groups ( Table  2) (http://www.idf.org/ metabolic syndrome).

A risk assessment  calculator that uses information from the Framingham Heart Study  was developed to predict a person’s chance of having a heart attack in  the next 10 years (http://cvdrisk.nhlbi.nih.gov/calculator.asp).
In 2013, the American Heart Association and the American  College of Cardiology introduced a new ASCVD risk estimator  (http://tools.cardiosource.org/ASCVD-Risk-Estimator).

Men in the lowest  quartiles of serum TT, calculated free testosterone (cFT) and SHBG at  baseline had the highest odds ratios for developing the MetS or DM Table 1: ATP III clinical identification of the metabolic syndrome  (http://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/files/docs/guidelines/atp3xsum.pdf) Parameters Measurement Waist circumference Male >102 cm (>40 in) Female >88 cm (>35 in) Triglycerides ≥150 mg dl−1 HDL cholesterol Male <40 mg dl−1 Female <50 mg dl−1 BP ≥130/≥85 mmHg Fasting glucose ≥110 mg dl−1 Source: National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute; National Institutes of Health;  US Department of Health and Human Services.

ATP: adult treatment panel; HDL: high  density lipoprotein; BP: blood pressure Table 2: International diabetes federation criteria for diagnosis of  metabolic syndrome (http://www.idf.org/metabolic syndrome) Central obesity (defined as waist circumference* with ethnicity specific values)  plus any two of the following four factors Raised  triglycerides≥150 mg dl−1 or Specific treatment for this lipid abnormality Reduced HDL  cholesterol<40 mg dl−1 in males <50 mg dl−1 in females or Specific treatment for this lipid abnormality Raised BP Systolic BP ≥130 or diastolic BP ≥85 mmHg or Treatment of previously diagnosed HTN Raised FPG FPG ≥100 mg dl−1 or Previously diagnosed type 2 DM If above 100 mg dl−1, OGTT is strongly recommended but is not  necessary to define presence of the syndrome Source: International Diabetes Federation.

TREATMENT OF THE METABOLIC SYNDROME Recommendations from the 2013 Consensus Conference held by  the IDF for management of the MetS include (http://www.idf.org/ metabolic syndrome): (1) patients should undergo a full cardiovascular  risk assessment (including smoking status) in conjunction with the  following: moderate calorie restriction (to achieve a 5%–10% loss of  body weight in the first year), moderate increase in physical activity,  change in dietary composition.

The  Food and Drug Administration in the United States has concluded that  the current evidence does not indicate significantly increased risk, but  trial data is needed (http://www.citizen.org/documents/2184_FDA%20 Denial%20of%20Petition_July%2016, %202014.pdf).
